Use 9x9 for benchmark

Now that 4x4 is too easy, it's time to move on to something harder.
This will be convenient because difficulty can be ratcheted up
gradually by removing one square at a time.

Here are some times running on a 2012 MBP:

Elapsed time: 79.283037s (29.438492s in 319 GCs)
Elapsed time: 76.251785s (28.548067s in 319 GCs)
Elapsed time: 73.628577s (27.994638s in 318 GCs)
Elapsed time: 80.264210s (31.539141s in 358 GCs)
Elapsed time: 79.808532s (31.391441s in 357 GCs)
Elapsed time: 81.097268s (29.375902s in 319 GCs)

The specific times are fairly unstable, though they all fall in the
70-80-ish range. What's interesting is how little time is spent in GC
as compared with the previous benchmark. Why is this?

Add and consolidate Sudoku tests

Now that everything is faster, add more 4x4 tests and consolidate some
of the 9x9 tests into more difficult versions.

Use reazon-sudoku-solve-4x4 in memory profiler

The 4x4 solver now runs fast enough to use it in the profiler.

A suitable replacement needs to be found for the benchmark, since the
4x4 solver is probably nearing the point of diminishing returns.

Precompute 4x4 Sudoku permutations

Previously, the 4x4 solver was effectively computing the permutations
of (1 2 3 4) over and over at runtime. A huge performance boost can be
gotten by computing the permutations once at compile time, then
running a disjunction of == calls to each of the permutations with
each of the blocks.

The resulting macro expansion is about 300 lines, and this is what it
looks like:

(reazon-run* (a1 a2 a3 a4 b1 b2 b3 b4 c1 c2 c3 c4 d1 d2 d3 d4)
  (reazon-disj
   (reazon-== (\` ((\, a1) (\, a2) (\, a3) (\, a4))) (quote (1 2 3 4)))
   (reazon-== (\` ((\, a1) (\, a2) (\, a3) (\, a4))) (quote (1 2 4 3)))
   (reazon-== (\` ((\, a1) (\, a2) (\, a3) (\, a4))) (quote (1 4 2 3)))
   (reazon-== (\` ((\, a1) (\, a2) (\, a3) (\, a4))) (quote (1 3 2 4)))
   (reazon-== (\` ((\, a1) (\, a2) (\, a3) (\, a4))) (quote (1 4 3 2)))
   (reazon-== (\` ((\, a1) (\, a2) (\, a3) (\, a4))) (quote (1 3 4 2)))
   (reazon-== (\` ((\, a1) (\, a2) (\, a3) (\, a4))) (quote (2 1 3 4)))
   (reazon-== (\` ((\, a1) (\, a2) (\, a3) (\, a4))) (quote (2 1 4 3)))
   (reazon-== (\` ((\, a1) (\, a2) (\, a3) (\, a4))) (quote (4 1 2 3)))
   (reazon-== (\` ((\, a1) (\, a2) (\, a3) (\, a4))) (quote (2 4 1 3)))
   (reazon-== (\` ((\, a1) (\, a2) (\, a3) (\, a4))) (quote (3 1 2 4)))
   (reazon-== (\` ((\, a1) (\, a2) (\, a3) (\, a4))) (quote (2 3 1 4)))
   (reazon-== (\` ((\, a1) (\, a2) (\, a3) (\, a4))) (quote (4 1 3 2)))
   (reazon-== (\` ((\, a1) (\, a2) (\, a3) (\, a4))) (quote (4 2 1 3)))
   (reazon-== (\` ((\, a1) (\, a2) (\, a3) (\, a4))) (quote (2 4 3 1)))
   (reazon-== (\` ((\, a1) (\, a2) (\, a3) (\, a4))) (quote (3 1 4 2)))
   (reazon-== (\` ((\, a1) (\, a2) (\, a3) (\, a4))) (quote (2 3 4 1)))
   (reazon-== (\` ((\, a1) (\, a2) (\, a3) (\, a4))) (quote (3 2 1 4)))
   (reazon-== (\` ((\, a1) (\, a2) (\, a3) (\, a4))) (quote (4 3 1 2)))
   (reazon-== (\` ((\, a1) (\, a2) (\, a3) (\, a4))) (quote (4 2 3 1)))
   (reazon-== (\` ((\, a1) (\, a2) (\, a3) (\, a4))) (quote (3 4 1 2)))
   (reazon-== (\` ((\, a1) (\, a2) (\, a3) (\, a4))) (quote (3 2 4 1)))
   (reazon-== (\` ((\, a1) (\, a2) (\, a3) (\, a4))) (quote (4 3 2 1)))
   (reazon-== (\` ((\, a1) (\, a2) (\, a3) (\, a4))) (quote (3 4 2 1))))
...
)

Unfortunately, this strategy doesn't seem to scale to the 9x9 case.
This is because there are just 24 permutations of a four-element list,
but 362880 for a nine-element list.

Running the 4x4 Sudoku benchmark on a 2012 MBP (where the Before time
uses the previous unrolling strategy):

Before:

Elapsed time: 24.264427s (16.165260s in 212 GCs)
Elapsed time: 24.282203s (16.141869s in 210 GCs)

After:

Elapsed time: 5.426367s (3.888877s in 58 GCs)
Elapsed time: 5.307984s (3.790005s in 57 GCs)

Note that we've gone from spending around 2/3 of time in GC to almost
3/4. Why is that?

Unroll Sudoku subseto calls

The Sudoku solvers were using the general `subseto` relation, but in
fact that generality is not needed: the groups of squares are
stipulated to contain only very specific items, and some speed can be
gained by taking advantage of this. A little elegance is thereby lost,
but oh well.

Running the 4x4 benchmark on a 2012 MBP:

Before:

Elapsed time: 31.900794s (20.630957s in 172 GCs)
Elapsed time: 31.963738s (20.649389s in 171 GCs)

After:

Elapsed time: 25.398572s (16.814765s in 143 GCs)
Elapsed time: 25.441664s (16.857431s in 142 GCs)

Cut nullo and conso  calls from subseto

This improves the Sudoku benchmark. On my crappy little Thinkpad:

Before:

Elapsed time: 84.860262s (49.587667s in 282 GCs)
Elapsed time: 85.333766s (49.972954s in 281 GCs)

After:

Elapsed time: 79.561496s (46.021752s in 258 GCs)
Elapsed time: 79.881404s (46.202112s in 254 GCs)

These relations make programs a little cleaner I guess, but is it
worth the hit to speed? I'm leaning towards no. Maybe it's only a
problem in hotspots.

Add solved 9x9 Sudoku tests

Recent efficiency improvements have made it possible to actually solve
some 9x9 Sudoku boards (albeit very easy ones). These still run slow,
and the whole test apparatus is slowed down, but it's worth it
overall (I think) as a concrete measure of progress.

Add 9x9 Sudoku test

It still takes too long to solve anything, but at least a failing
board can be rejected reasonably quickly.

Rewrite reazon-fresh to avoid recursion

Apparently the byte compiler chokes on macro calls that are nested too
deep. That can be avoided by calling the fresh vars in one fell swoop.

This change appears to have no effect on performance.
Add commented out Sudoku 9x9 test

Cut conso call from membero

With this change, the Sudoko benchmark goes from ~42s to ~36s, a 14%
improvement. Perhaps relation calls are more expensive than function
calls in typical programming, or maybe the Sudoku benchmark is just an
extreme case.

Cut repeated fresh variables from membero

Measuring times with the Sudoku benchmark, which makes heavy use of
subseto and therefore also of membero:

Before:

Elapsed time: 66.872376s (44.716378s in 349 GCs)
Elapsed time: 67.323865s (44.929168s in 352 GCs)

After:

Elapsed time: 42.930116s (27.809902s in 216 GCs)
Elapsed time: 42.856743s (27.801893s in 217 GCs)

That's an improvement of about 1/3!
